@autobuild-instrumentation @observability
Feature: AutoBuild Instrumentation and Context Reduction
  As an AutoBuild operator
  I want structured observability events emitted at every significant point in a run
    and role-specific minimal digests replacing the full rules bundle
  So that I can measure prefill impact, compare prompt profiles, and tune the GB10 stack

  Background:
    Given the AutoBuild pipeline is configured and ready to execute tasks
    And the event emission layer is enabled

  # ============================================================================
  # GROUP A: Key Examples
  # ============================================================================

  # Why: Core instrumentation contract — every LLM call produces a structured event with required fields
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: An LLM call during an AutoBuild run emits a complete llm.call event
    Given an AutoBuild run is in progress
    When the Player agent makes an LLM call
    Then an "llm.call" event should be emitted
    And the event should include a non-null "run_id"
    And the event should include a non-null "input_tokens" count
    And the event should include a non-null "output_tokens" count
    And the event should include a non-null "latency_ms" value
    And the event should include a non-null "prompt_profile"
    And the event should include the "agent_role" as "player"

  # Why: Core contract — tool executions are captured with exit code and latency
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A tool execution during an AutoBuild run emits a tool.exec event
    Given an AutoBuild run is in progress
    When the Player agent executes a shell command
    Then a "tool.exec" event should be emitted
    And the event should include the "tool_name"
    And the event should include the "exit_code"
    And the event should include "latency_ms"
    And the event should include truncated "stdout_tail" and "stderr_tail"

  # Why: Core contract — task lifecycle is tracked from start to completion
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Task lifecycle events are emitted for a successful task
    Given an AutoBuild run starts for a task
    When the task completes successfully
    Then a "task.started" event should have been emitted at the beginning
    And a "task.completed" event should be emitted at the end
    And the "task.completed" event should include "turn_count"
    And the "task.completed" event should include "diff_stats"
    And the "task.completed" event should include "verification_status" as "passed"
    And the "task.completed" event should include the "prompt_profile" used

  # Why: Core contract — failed tasks emit failure events with categorised reasons
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A failed task emits a task.failed event with a valid failure category
    Given an AutoBuild run starts for a task
    When the task fails due to a test failure
    Then a "task.failed" event should be emitted
    And the "failure_category" should be "test_failure"
    And the "failure_category" should be from the controlled vocabulary

  # Why: Graphiti context retrievals must be observable for measuring retrieval cost
  @key-example
  Scenario: A Graphiti context retrieval emits a graphiti.query event
    Given an AutoBuild run is in progress with Graphiti enabled
    When the context loader retrieves context from Graphiti
    Then a "graphiti.query" event should be emitted
    And the event should include "query_type"
    And the event should include "items_returned"
    And the event should include "tokens_injected"
    And the event should include "latency_ms"

  # Why: Role-specific digests are the foundation of context reduction
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Maximum digest size is 700 tokens as stated in acceptance criteria
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: The Player role receives a digest under the token limit
    Given the prompt profile is "digest_only"
    When the Player agent's system prompt is assembled
    Then the injected digest should be the Player-specific digest
    And the digest token count should be under 700 tokens

  # Why: All four roles must have distinct digests
  @key-example
  Scenario: Each agent role has a distinct role-specific digest
    Given role-specific digests are configured
    Then the Player digest should exist and define implementation rules
    And the Coach digest should exist and define validation rules
    And the Resolver digest should exist and define root cause analysis rules
    And the Router digest should exist and define model selection rules
    And no two digests should be identical

  # Why: Prompt profile tagging is the key to A/B comparisons
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Every LLM call is tagged with the active prompt profile
    Given the prompt profile is set to "digest+graphiti"
    When any agent makes an LLM call during the run
    Then every "llm.call" event should have "prompt_profile" set to "digest+graphiti"

