  # Why: Tool names and arguments could contain injection attempts
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Tool.exec events sanitise tool name and arguments against injection
    Given the Player agent executes a command with shell metacharacters in the tool name
    When the "tool.exec" event is assembled
    Then the "tool_name" should be sanitised
    And the "cmd" field should not allow shell injection through event data

  # Why: stdout/stderr may contain secrets that were not in the command itself
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Tool.exec event truncation removes secrets from stdout and stderr tails
    Given a tool execution produces stdout containing an API key
    When the "tool.exec" event is assembled
    Then the "stdout_tail" should have known secret patterns redacted
    And the "stderr_tail" should have known secret patterns redacted

  # Why: Parallel workers must not corrupt shared instrumentation state
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Concurrent wave workers emit independent events without data corruption
    Given a wave is running with 3 parallel workers
    When all 3 workers emit "tool.exec" events simultaneously
    Then each event should have the correct "task_id" for its worker
    And no event should contain fields from a different worker's execution

  # Why: Multiple LLM calls in a single turn must be distinguishable
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Multiple LLM calls within a single turn produce distinct events
    Given the Player agent makes 2 LLM calls within the same turn
    When both "llm.call" events are emitted
    Then the events should have distinct timestamps
    And both should share the same "run_id" and "attempt"
    And the "input_tokens" should reflect each call independently

  # Why: NATS failure during a run should not lose events
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Events fall back to local log when NATS drops mid-run
    Given an AutoBuild run is emitting events to NATS
    When the NATS connection is lost mid-run
    Then subsequent events should be written to the local structured log file
    And no events should be silently dropped
    And a warning should be logged about the NATS fallback

  # Why: Event emission must not add latency to the LLM call path
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Event emission does not block the LLM call critical path
    Given an AutoBuild run is in progress
    When the Player agent makes an LLM call
    Then the "llm.call" event should be emitted asynchronously
    And the LLM call should not wait for event delivery confirmation before proceeding
